18/03/2003
SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) -- Security Minister Barisa Colak says there was no reason for concern over the security situation in the country following the assassination of Serbian Prime Minister Zoran Djindjic. 
Speaking Monday (17 March), Colak said he was in regular contact with the members of the BiH State Border Service (SBS), BiH Interpol and the entity police forces. 
BiH SBS says control over border checkpoints with Serbia-Montenegro has been tightened.
In other news, the Stability Pact for South Eastern Europe's Special Co-ordinator, Erhard Busek, met Monday in Sarajevo with High Representative Paddy Ashdown. 
They discussed the need for faster implementation of reforms, among other things. 
Busek later met with BiH Presidency Chairman Mirko Sarovic and Foreign Minister Mladen Ivanic. 
(OHR Sources - 18/03/03; PBS BiH, BH Radio 1, Onasa, SRNA, BBC - 17/03/03)
